00:00:46.690 --> 00:00:49.130
First off, Luna Barbara asks,
if you were giving advice

00:00:49.130 --> 00:00:51.840
to a web developer trying to
start up accessibility initiatives

00:00:51.840 --> 00:00:54.320
and projects at their current
job, what advice would you give?

00:00:55.333 --> 00:00:57.420
 RYAN BRACEY: Hey
there, I'm Ryan Bracey.

00:00:57.420 --> 00:01:00.080
If you're looking to introduce
accessibility initiatives

00:01:00.080 --> 00:01:02.680
at your company,
the first thing you're going to want

00:01:02.680 --> 00:01:06.580
to do is educate yourself on the
basic principles and guidelines

00:01:06.580 --> 00:01:09.320
of the Web Content Accessibility
Guidelines or WCAG.

00:01:10.340 --> 00:01:14.150
As soon as you introduce this
initiative, you're naturally going

00:01:14.150 --> 00:01:17.970
to just become your company's
go-to accessibility expert.

00:01:17.970 --> 00:01:21.580
So building a really solid
knowledge foundation is going

00:01:21.580 --> 00:01:24.380
to be really critical
to your success here.

00:01:24.380 --> 00:01:27.140
It's also important to
remember that accessibility

00:01:27.140 --> 00:01:30.400
isn't a perfect science,
it's more like a moving target.

00:01:30.400 --> 00:01:33.360
So staying up to date on
emerging trends is going

00:01:33.360 --> 00:01:35.380
to be really important as well.

00:01:35.380 --> 00:01:40.350
Make sure you participate in meetups,
attend conferences like this one,

00:01:40.350 --> 00:01:43.240
and join some community
Slack channels.

00:01:43.240 --> 00:01:47.580
All of this is going to really
give you invaluable knowledge

00:01:47.580 --> 00:01:51.410
and insight as things
evolve over time.

00:01:51.410 --> 00:01:55.160
Once you have that foundation set,
and you go to present this initiative

00:01:55.160 --> 00:02:00.400
to your team, remember you're now
your company's accessibility advocate

00:02:00.400 --> 00:02:03.420
and your team is going to be
looking to you for guidance.

00:02:03.420 --> 00:02:07.300
So start educating them on
the importance, the benefits,

00:02:07.300 --> 00:02:10.710
and the consequences of accessibility
compliance, and then try

00:02:10.710 --> 00:02:14.070
to connect these principles back
to what their specific roles

00:02:14.070 --> 00:02:15.980
and deliverables are
within their teams.

00:02:17.010 --> 00:02:21.460
You'll also want to set some clear
accessibility goals for your company,

00:02:21.460 --> 00:02:24.110
and then start helping the
different departments develop

00:02:24.110 --> 00:02:27.370
their own processes on how to
best integrate accessibility

00:02:27.370 --> 00:02:28.370
into their own work.

00:02:29.360 --> 00:02:32.920
Most of all, you really always
want to be communicating.

00:02:32.920 --> 00:02:36.390
Try to create a dedicated
space such as a Slack channel

00:02:36.390 --> 00:02:39.100
if you have a company,
Slack workspace,

00:02:39.100 --> 00:02:42.690
somewhere where you can share
knowledge, ask questions,

00:02:42.690 --> 00:02:44.800
and just foster discussion
amongst each other.

00:02:46.020 --> 00:02:48.762
By following this advice
and constantly advocating

00:02:48.763 --> 00:02:51.202
for accessibility
within your company,

00:02:51.203 --> 00:02:53.640
you'll be able to
create a significant

00:02:53.640 --> 00:02:58.020
and positive impact on just
the overall inclusivity

00:02:58.020 --> 00:02:59.460
of the work your company creates.

00:03:00.300 --> 00:03:02.430
 SPEAKER 1: Tom asks,
how would a deaf or hard

00:03:02.430 --> 00:03:05.230
of hearing person know if captions
omitted words, particularly

00:03:05.230 --> 00:03:07.060
if the speaker is not visible?

00:03:07.060 --> 00:03:10.700
I am concerned about the potential
for trouble when seeing do,

00:03:10.700 --> 00:03:12.380
when the speaker
actually meant do not.

00:03:13.900 --> 00:03:15.850
 JOE DOLSON: Hi,
this is Joe Dolson.

00:03:15.850 --> 00:03:19.320
This is why accurate
captions are important.

00:03:19.320 --> 00:03:22.510
The WCAG guidelines don't
explicitly say that captions need

00:03:22.510 --> 00:03:27.080
to be accurate, but I'd argue
that if a caption isn't accurate,

00:03:27.080 --> 00:03:28.720
then it isn't a caption.

00:03:28.720 --> 00:03:33.130
The definition of a caption
in HTML5 is, a transcription

00:03:33.130 --> 00:03:37.040
or translation of the dialogue,
sound effects, relevant musical cues,

00:03:37.040 --> 00:03:40.500
and other relevant audio information
when sound is unavailable

00:03:40.500 --> 00:03:41.830
or not clearly audible.

00:03:43.070 --> 00:03:45.707
Transcription is a
precise reproduction

00:03:45.708 --> 00:03:47.750
of the meaningful spoken text.

00:03:47.750 --> 00:03:49.554
Translation is a
faithful reproduction

00:03:49.555 --> 00:03:52.390
of the meaning of that text
in another language.

00:03:52.390 --> 00:03:55.690
In either case,
accuracy is a fundamental part

00:03:55.690 --> 00:03:57.460
of what makes that text meaningful.

00:03:58.480 --> 00:04:03.270
Live captioning, because it is done
in real time, will contain mistakes.

00:04:03.270 --> 00:04:07.150
But for any pre-recorded video,
if you don't take the opportunity

00:04:07.150 --> 00:04:11.660
to ensure accuracy, you're explicitly
discriminating against deaf

00:04:11.660 --> 00:04:12.940
and hard of hearing populations.

