00:08:59.300 --> 00:09:02.040
 SPEAKER 1: Taeke asks,
Dark Mode, Yay or Nay?

00:09:02.040 --> 00:09:05.920
Is Dark Mode a fancy feature
or a web accessibility must?

00:09:05.920 --> 00:09:10.230
 NICK: Hopefully you have seen the
WordPress Accessibility Day website,

00:09:10.230 --> 00:09:14.400
and we created this with
Dark Mode and Light Mode.

00:09:14.400 --> 00:09:17.900
I can toggle this off,
and you get the Light Mode setting

00:09:17.900 --> 00:09:19.250
and then toggle it back on.

00:09:21.460 --> 00:09:27.360
With Dark Mode, it's best if
we listen to the user's request

00:09:27.360 --> 00:09:32.400
so you can set prefers Dark Color
Scheme, prefers Light Color Scheme,

00:09:32.400 --> 00:09:33.760
and enable that.

00:09:33.760 --> 00:09:35.740
And we can do that
via media queries,

00:09:35.740 --> 00:09:38.390
and we can also get that
information in JavaScript.

00:09:39.830 --> 00:09:43.200
With this website, we also added
the ability to switch modes,

00:09:43.200 --> 00:09:45.210
and that's not necessary.

00:09:45.210 --> 00:09:50.120
And in some cases, a lot of users
don't really switch back and forth

00:09:50.120 --> 00:09:52.730
between different things,
but having the ability

00:09:52.730 --> 00:09:57.290
to honor the user's request is
important for accessibility.

00:09:58.500 --> 00:10:04.230
I did a big talk about this with the
WordPress Accessibility Meetup Group.

00:10:06.090 --> 00:10:08.960
So in the WordPress Accessibility
Meetup Group, you can search

00:10:08.960 --> 00:10:12.400
for past events and find Dark,
Light, and Inverted Developers Guide

00:10:12.400 --> 00:10:13.910
to Color Modes with Nick Croft.

00:10:13.910 --> 00:10:16.950
It's got some information
on here about that.

00:10:16.950 --> 00:10:21.350
And then if you scroll in
and look for the comments,

00:10:21.350 --> 00:10:26.620
there's a comment that says,
find the recap here, which takes you

00:10:26.620 --> 00:10:29.510
to the page on
equalizeddigital.com.

00:10:31.350 --> 00:10:35.310
On this page, it's also dark, light,
and inverted, developers guide

00:10:35.310 --> 00:10:37.600
to color modes with Nick Croft.

00:10:37.600 --> 00:10:41.410
And got a little bit of information
about here, about the meetup,

00:10:41.410 --> 00:10:43.760
and then down at the bottom,
you can watch the recording.

00:10:43.760 --> 00:10:47.740
In this recording, I go into a lot
of details about the importance

00:10:47.740 --> 00:10:50.640
of using media queries
to honor user requests,

00:10:50.640 --> 00:10:53.490
and how that is an
accessibility bonus for people.

00:10:54.710 --> 00:10:57.800
For me, I prefer dark
mode as a personal thing.

00:10:57.800 --> 00:11:02.250
And it is not detrimental to
my ability to consume content.

00:11:02.250 --> 00:11:06.210
For some other users,
dark mode is extremely important

00:11:06.210 --> 00:11:08.340
to their ability
to consume content.

00:11:08.340 --> 00:11:13.860
Light sensitivity and other
disabilities can make it difficult

00:11:13.860 --> 00:11:18.400
for them to use a very bright
background like this with white text,

00:11:18.400 --> 00:11:21.500
where a dark mode background,
more like what we have

00:11:21.500 --> 00:11:26.960
on the WordPress Accessibility
Day website, works great for them.

00:11:26.960 --> 00:11:32.290
So I do believe that it is
a web accessibility benefit,

00:11:32.290 --> 00:11:35.280
but it is not currently something
that will cause your site to fail

00:11:35.280 --> 00:11:35.960
and accessibility.

00:11:35.960 --> 00:11:38.970
So this is a bonus
that we give to users.

00:11:38.970 --> 00:11:42.200
As things evolve and grow in the
future, we may see changes to that,

00:11:42.200 --> 00:11:46.440
but right now it's definitely worth
investigating and starting to use.

00:11:46.440 --> 00:11:47.160
Hope that helps.

00:11:47.800 --> 00:11:49.420
 SPEAKER 1: Chris asks,
do you have any data

00:11:49.420 --> 00:11:52.570
about motor function disability
being able to mouse and hit targets?

00:11:53.433 --> 00:11:56.090
 JOE: This is a complicated
question to unpack.

00:11:56.090 --> 00:11:59.680
First, what data is important here?

00:12:00.870 --> 00:12:02.960
There's data about
people who have gross

00:12:02.960 --> 00:12:06.870
or fine motor function impairments,
but that doesn't tell us much

00:12:06.870 --> 00:12:09.080
about their use of a computer.

00:12:09.080 --> 00:12:10.850
We could go looking for
data on what percentage

00:12:10.850 --> 00:12:15.820
of these users are able to use a
mouse, but practically speaking,

00:12:15.820 --> 00:12:17.190
that's most of them.

00:12:17.190 --> 00:12:20.400
A lot of standard mice have a high
precision mode that slows travel

00:12:20.400 --> 00:12:22.590
and makes it easier
to target objects.

00:12:22.590 --> 00:12:24.670
Assistive technology
includes a wide variety

00:12:24.670 --> 00:12:28.800
of different pointing devices,
including track balls, joysticks,

00:12:28.800 --> 00:12:30.160
switches, track pads.

00:12:31.540 --> 00:12:33.860
All of those can be used to
point at an object on a screen

00:12:33.860 --> 00:12:35.360
and hit a target.

00:12:35.360 --> 00:12:39.660
As a result, people with motor
disabilities are quite likely

00:12:39.660 --> 00:12:42.380
to be able to use a mouse,
at least in some sense of the word.

00:12:44.120 --> 00:12:46.470
I wrote an article a few
years ago about the myth

00:12:46.470 --> 00:12:48.640
of the keyboard-only user.

00:12:48.640 --> 00:12:53.340
We work very hard in accessibility to
make everything keyboard accessible

00:12:53.340 --> 00:12:56.160
so that you can use every
single part of a website

00:12:56.160 --> 00:12:57.920
or an application
using the keyboard.

00:12:59.250 --> 00:13:01.980
However, this isn't really
about some theoretical user

00:13:01.980 --> 00:13:03.840
who can't use a pointing device.

00:13:03.840 --> 00:13:06.750
It's about time and efficiency.

00:13:06.750 --> 00:13:11.320
People with motor disabilities may
struggle to change interface modes.

00:13:11.320 --> 00:13:13.910
If you're currently
using a pointing device,

00:13:13.910 --> 00:13:16.960
you use the pointing device, but if
you're currently using a keyboard,

00:13:16.960 --> 00:13:20.880
maybe it costs you 15 minutes
and a spoon to switch modes.

00:13:20.880 --> 00:13:26.980
So if a control can only be used
with a pointer, you can use it.

00:13:26.980 --> 00:13:27.980
But what's the cost?

00:13:29.000 --> 00:13:31.070
The point of making everything
keyboard accessible is

00:13:31.070 --> 00:13:34.980
that a user should be able to
use any control with the tool

00:13:34.980 --> 00:13:35.980
of their choice.

00:13:36.800 --> 00:13:39.210
So getting back to
that data question,

00:13:39.210 --> 00:13:44.230
I think the most useful data would
be an appraisal of time lost.

00:13:44.230 --> 00:13:48.200
How much time has it cost this user
because they could only use a control

00:13:48.200 --> 00:13:49.590
with a mouse?

00:13:49.590 --> 00:13:53.180
Even if each individual action
is only a few seconds lost,

00:13:53.180 --> 00:13:55.760
that aggregate loss of
time could be enormous.

00:13:57.280 --> 00:14:00.560
Data about motor function
impairments that impact the use

00:14:00.560 --> 00:14:04.820
of computers is underrepresented
in common data sets.

00:14:04.820 --> 00:14:07.890
The CDC,
or Center for Disease Control,

00:14:07.890 --> 00:14:10.470
publishes a data
collection standard.

00:14:10.470 --> 00:14:12.750
It's the six standard
disability questions

00:14:12.750 --> 00:14:15.020
or the Washington group questions.

00:14:15.020 --> 00:14:19.970
That doesn't capture this
information in any way.

00:14:19.970 --> 00:14:24.160
It is focused on motor
disabilities that impact walking

00:14:24.160 --> 00:14:28.260
and moving around or showering
and specific activities,

00:14:28.260 --> 00:14:29.440
but it doesn't cover computers.

00:14:30.510 --> 00:14:33.830
So effectively, I don't have
any useful data about this.

00:14:33.830 --> 00:14:37.060
If I was looking for it, I'd be
comparing the time to complete tasks

00:14:37.060 --> 00:14:39.472
for users with motor
function impairments

00:14:39.473 --> 00:14:41.080
against a control baseline,

00:14:41.080 --> 00:14:44.740
so that we could really get a
sense of what the overall time cost

00:14:44.740 --> 00:14:45.540
for these users is.

00:14:47.633 --> 00:14:50.190
 SPEAKER 1: And Arnetia asks,
there are so many WordPress themes

00:14:50.190 --> 00:14:52.230
to choose from, and I would
assume that some are built

00:14:52.230 --> 00:14:54.990
with accessibility in
mind while others are not.

00:14:54.990 --> 00:14:57.930
Do you have any tips for finding and
choosing a more accessible theme?

00:14:57.930 --> 00:15:00.600
What criteria should average
WordPress users look for

00:15:00.600 --> 00:15:01.360
when choosing a theme?

00:15:02.067 --> 00:15:05.490
 AMBER: A good place to start
is looking at the requirements

00:15:05.490 --> 00:15:08.570
of the accessibility ready tag.

00:15:08.570 --> 00:15:11.700
The accessibility ready tag is
something I think developers

00:15:11.700 --> 00:15:15.080
who are submitting free plugins
WordPress.org can optionally go

00:15:15.080 --> 00:15:17.040
through a review in
order to get that tag.

00:15:17.040 --> 00:15:20.040
And I'm not saying you have to
start with one of those themes.

00:15:20.040 --> 00:15:24.520
What I'm saying is you can
go in the developer handbook

00:15:24.520 --> 00:15:28.270
and you can find what the
criteria is in order for someone

00:15:28.270 --> 00:15:30.420
to get the accessibility ready tag.

00:15:30.420 --> 00:15:33.550
And then that might tell you what
things you would want to look for

00:15:33.550 --> 00:15:35.200
in a theme as a baseline.

00:15:35.200 --> 00:15:39.870
Now, I want to be really clear, like
those are really just a baseline.

00:15:39.870 --> 00:15:45.390
It's not going to give you 100%
the best most accessible starter

00:15:45.390 --> 00:15:49.060
if you only look for those things,
but I think that is a good place

00:15:49.060 --> 00:15:49.870
to start.

00:15:49.870 --> 00:15:53.490
Things that I would look for if
I'm assessing a theme is one,

00:15:53.490 --> 00:15:56.260
does it have skip to content links?

00:15:56.260 --> 00:16:00.470
Two, does it have a
clear focus indicator?

00:16:00.470 --> 00:16:03.850
So you'd hit the tab key
and you would just tab

00:16:03.850 --> 00:16:05.870
through the website
from top to bottom.

00:16:05.870 --> 00:16:08.390
You want to be able to see
that outline and then you want

00:16:08.390 --> 00:16:09.910
to see that it goes in order.

00:16:11.060 --> 00:16:14.260
Now, if you know CSS, and you're
comfortable with editing CSS,

00:16:14.260 --> 00:16:16.840
you can pick a theme
that doesn't have that

00:16:16.840 --> 00:16:20.350
because that's maybe a
two second fix, right?

00:16:20.350 --> 00:16:22.100
To add that outline in.

00:16:22.100 --> 00:16:24.720
But if you're someone who
doesn't know CSS and you're going

00:16:24.720 --> 00:16:28.640
to use a theme out of the box,
then you would want to try

00:16:28.640 --> 00:16:30.270
and find a theme that
already has a theme.

00:16:30.270 --> 00:16:35.860
Another thing that I would do is I
would test out the navigation menus.

00:16:35.860 --> 00:16:39.600
And most of the
non-block based themes

00:16:39.600 --> 00:16:43.210
and navigation menus are
controlled by the theme.

00:16:43.210 --> 00:16:47.390
So you want to make sure that
you can access all of every item

00:16:47.390 --> 00:16:48.720
in the drop-down.

00:16:48.720 --> 00:16:51.690
If you don't know how to do
styles, then of course you want

00:16:51.690 --> 00:16:54.710
to look for a theme that
has good color contrast.

00:16:54.710 --> 00:16:58.660
If you know how to do styles,
then I sort of disregard

00:16:58.660 --> 00:17:01.460
any sort of color contrast issues
in a theme because I just think,

00:17:01.460 --> 00:17:04.020
OK, well,
I'll just recolor it when I use it.

00:17:05.680 --> 00:17:12.400
I would say in general, really
trying to separate what you need

00:17:12.400 --> 00:17:17.030
from that theme versus what's
going to come in a plug-in.

00:17:18.770 --> 00:17:23.060
So there are some themes out
there that are built with...

00:17:24.330 --> 00:17:29.520
they have custom builders or it's
a theme and it includes a form.

00:17:29.520 --> 00:17:32.850
I would always recommend that
someone go choose a form plug-in,

00:17:32.850 --> 00:17:35.510
and use a form plug-in,
instead of allowing their theme

00:17:35.510 --> 00:17:37.960
to create their contact
form, for example.

00:17:37.960 --> 00:17:40.970
You're more likely to have
better accessibility output

00:17:40.970 --> 00:17:44.750
if you choose a plug-in that focuses
on that one thing versus trying

00:17:44.750 --> 00:17:47.360
to get a theme that can do
all those things for you.

00:17:49.040 --> 00:17:54.460
Another thing along those same lines
is, I would tend to choose a theme

00:17:54.460 --> 00:18:00.370
that is more basic, and I don't
mean that it can't be styled

00:18:00.370 --> 00:18:01.740
and look really professional.

00:18:01.740 --> 00:18:05.010
It can be styled and look really
professional, but choose a theme

00:18:05.010 --> 00:18:08.450
that doesn't have a lot
of interactive elements.

00:18:08.450 --> 00:18:13.440
It doesn't need to have things
fading up as you scroll or flying in

00:18:13.440 --> 00:18:15.310
from the left or the right.

00:18:15.310 --> 00:18:17.070
Maybe don't have a carousel.

00:18:17.070 --> 00:18:21.700
There's a lot of data out there
that carousels are not required

00:18:21.700 --> 00:18:24.820
and in fact people don't interact
with them or they don't like them

00:18:24.820 --> 00:18:27.250
or they cause problems on mobile.

00:18:27.250 --> 00:18:31.220
So I wouldn't choose a
theme where the whole top

00:18:31.220 --> 00:18:34.840
of the homepage won't look good
if there's not a carousel there.

00:18:34.840 --> 00:18:36.360
I hope that gives you
a good starting point.

